## Data Flow Examples

### Example 1: Login Flow

```
USER INTERACTION:
User enters email & password in Login.jsx
    ↓
Clicks "Login" button
    ↓
Form submits via Formik

COMPONENT LOGIC:
Login.jsx calls:
    const response = await ProductService.login({
      email: "user@test.com",
      password: "password123"
    })
    ↓
ProductService.login() calls:
    api.post("/auth/login", credentials)
    ↓
axios.js REQUEST INTERCEPTOR:
    Prepares request (no token yet for login)
    ↓
BACKEND:
    POST /api/auth/login
    Validates credentials
    Returns: { token: "jwt...", user: {...} }
    ↓
axios.js RESPONSE INTERCEPTOR:
    Processes successful response
    ↓
Login.jsx receives response
    ↓
Calls AuthService.login(token, user):
    localStorage.setItem("token", token)
    localStorage.setItem("user", user)
    setToken(token)
    setUser(user)
    ↓
AuthContext state updates
    ↓
React Router navigates to /dashboard
    ↓
Dashboard renders:
    ProtectedRoute checks token → exists → Renders Dashboard
    ↓
Dashboard fetches data:
    ProductService.getAllProducts() with token in header
    ↓
Displays products to user
```

### Example 2: Add Product Flow

```
USER INTERACTION:
User clicks "Add Product" button
    ↓
Navigates to /products/add
    ↓
AddProduct.jsx renders

COMPONENT INITIALIZATION:
AddProduct mounts
    ↓
Formik initializes form with empty values:
    { name: "", price: "", quantity: "", manufacturer: "" }
    ↓
Yup schema validates on change

USER FILLS FORM:
User enters product details
    ↓
Formik updates state on each field change
    ↓
Validation runs (Yup schema)
    ↓
Submit button enabled when all fields valid

USER SUBMITS:
Clicks "Add Product" button
    ↓
Formik runs onSubmit handler:
    ↓
AddProduct.jsx calls:
